<h2 id="download" style="text-align:center;border-bottom:none;padding-bottom:0">Download Sonic Encore</h2>

The <strong>Final Build</strong> released at SAGE 2023 is the complete version — all 6 zones, 12 acts, every boss encounter, and all 6 characters included. This is a portable game: extract the archive and run it directly, no installer needed.

<div style="display:flex;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:8px;margin:12px auto">
<a href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1rld9vHz5yX2sBbIpC9cZD5MBEPpCOyrJ/view" class="su-button" style="background:#1F50EA;border-radius:6px;margin:0" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Download for Windows</a>
</div>

<div class="details-box">
<h3>How to Install Sonic Encore</h3>
<div class="details-grid">
<details>
<summary>Windows</summary>
<p>Download the ZIP file from Google Drive. Extract it to any folder on your PC using Windows Explorer or 7-Zip. Open the extracted folder and double-click the game executable to play. No additional software or dependencies required.</p>
</details>
</div>
</div>

<h2>From Learning Project to Finished Fan Game</h2>

Sonic Encore started in 2019 when lordgimpet set out to learn programming and level design. Building a 3D Sonic fan game seemed like a fun challenge, and what began as an experiment quickly grew into something the community took notice of. Public demos at <strong>SAGE 2021 and SAGE 2022</strong> built anticipation, and the project attracted contributions from <strong>notable fan game developers</strong> including Posquen (creator of Sonic Calamity), Gry (creator of Sonic GT), supersonic68 (Bumper Framework), and Lucas Rodr&iacute;guez (Ring Engine).

The developer described the game as <strong>"a greatest hits of some of my favorite levels"</strong> — no original story, no custom soundtrack, just pure gameplay built around reimagining classic zones in three dimensions. When the Final Build dropped at SAGE 2023, lordgimpet confirmed that "everything I set as a goal for completion has been achieved," marking the end of the project's development road.

<center style="margin:28px 0"><iframe title="Sonic Encore Final Build gameplay" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/AC_63d0lqb8" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></center>

For a game born out of a desire to learn, the end result punches well above its weight. There was even a period when the community doubted the project would ever be finished — but lordgimpet proved them wrong.

<h2>Momentum-Driven 3D Controls</h2>

Where Sonic Encore really shines is in how it handles speed. The momentum system rewards skillful play — <strong>you build velocity through slopes, spin dashes, and level geometry</strong> rather than hitting scripted speed boosters. Chaining momentum across entire sections feels natural when you get it right, and the levels are designed to let skilled players maintain flow without stopping.

Your moveset includes <strong>spin dash, drop dash, homing attack, stomp, and ring dash</strong>. The stomp deserves special attention: unlike most Sonic games where slamming into the ground kills your speed, Sonic Encore's stomp <strong>preserves your momentum</strong>. Hit the ground at full speed and you keep rolling. The community widely considers this one of the game's smartest design choices.

The 3D loops are manual and physics-driven — they feel satisfying to execute rather than being automated spectacles. Several content creators have gone as far as claiming that <strong>Sonic Encore controls better than Sonic GT</strong>, which is significant praise given GT's standing in the fan game community.

That said, there is a noticeable weak point: <strong>low-speed control feels stiff</strong>. When standing still or barely moving, Sonic is rigid and unresponsive. Fortunately, the wide open level design rarely demands precision platforming at a standstill — once you build speed, everything flows.

<h2>All 6 Zones Explored</h2>

Every zone is pulled from a different classic Sonic title and rebuilt as a <strong>wide, exploration-friendly 3D environment</strong>. Levels are large — comparable to Sonic Heroes in scope — with individual runs lasting 8 to 12 minutes depending on how much you explore.

